The `design/` folder sits next to the orchestrator because it is a build-time
input to a specific helper (`renderOgImage/loadDesignSource`) and is only
read, never re-exported. Keeping it inside `src/service/socialShare/`
guarantees Next.js never emits it as a route (anything under `public/` would
be routable; anything under `src/service/` is not).

## Prerequisites

- `public/expo-wave.png` must exist at its current path. It is already present
  ŌĆö no work required, but the render script depends on it for the shipped asset
  referenced by the generated OG image's implicit alt content. If absent, the
  root intent's Expo-everywhere outcome breaks before this plan runs.
- `@playwright/test` is already a devDependency (1.50.1). The raw `playwright`
  package adds the chromium launcher API; step 5 installs it.
- The Chromium browser binary must be present on any machine that executes
  `npm run build` ŌĆö `npm ci` does not install it. The canonical command is
  `npx playwright install chromium` (add `--with-deps` on Linux to also
  install the OS libraries Chromium needs: libnss3, libnspr4, libatk1.0-0,
  libatspi2.0-0, libxkbcommon0, etc.). Local dev machines must run this
  command once after a fresh clone. GitHub Actions runners are fresh every
  job, so the workflow itself must install the browser ŌĆö step 6 adds the
  step that satisfies this prerequisite automatically for CI.
- Node 22 + npm 10 on the build host (per root environment). `node:fs/promises`
  and native ESM are assumed.
- The dev server on port 3001 is not a prerequisite for the build ŌĆö `og.png`
  is rendered from a static `file://` URL, not the running site. The dev
  server is only used in step 9 for QA visual verification.

## Plan

### 1. Lift types and centralize the ogImage config

Read: `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`, `coding-playbook/architecture/folder-structure`

- [x] 1a. Create `src/types/socialShare.ts` exporting an `OgImageConfig` type
      with fields: `title: string`, `description: string`, `siteName: string`,
      `url: string` (canonical site URL), `imageUrl: string` (absolute URL of
      og.png on the deployed site), `imagePath: string` (site-root path, e.g.
      `/og.png`), `width: 1200`, `height: 630`, `alt: string`. Width and
      height are literal types so TypeScript rejects any drift from the spec
      dimensions. No runtime logic in this file.
- [x] 1b. Create `src/service/socialShare/ogImageConfig/index.ts` ŌĆö a default
      export returning a frozen `OgImageConfig`. Hard-coded constants from the
      spec and handoff:
        - `title`: `"AIDEMD.DEV ŌĆö intent is the source"`
        - `description`: `"A byte-faithful record of the .aide methodology. Every .aide is a contract ŌĆö scope, outcomes, guardrails ŌĆö that cascades through your stack."`
        - `siteName`: `"AIDEMD.DEV"`
        - `url`: `"https://aidemd.dev/"`
        - `imageUrl`: `"https://aidemd.dev/og.png"`
        - `imagePath`: `"/og.png"`
        - `width`: `1200`
        - `height`: `630`
        - `alt`: `"Expo, the AIDEMD mascot, waving next to the tagline 'intent is the source.'"`
      The alt string is byte-identical to the spec's "Good examples" section;
      drift here re-leaks the abandoned mascot names.
- [x] 1c. Create `src/service/socialShare/index.ts` ŌĆö the orchestrator. It
      imports `ogImageConfig`, calls it once at module load, and exports both
      the resolved config as a named export `ogImage` and as the default
      export. No render-script wiring here; the orchestrator's single
      responsibility is handing the metadata config to `app/layout.tsx`.
      JSDoc on the orchestrator names its consumer explicitly and notes that
      the render script at `renderOgImage` is a sibling helper reached only
      via npm scripts, never imported by this orchestrator (keeps Playwright
      out of the Next build graph).

