### 3. Self-host JetBrains Mono woff2 files

Read: `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`, `coding-playbook/architecture/folder-structure`

- [x] 3a. Download the four JetBrains Mono weights (400/500/600/700) as woff2
      from the official `JetBrains/JetBrainsMono` GitHub releases (latest
      tagged release) ŌĆö `JetBrainsMono-Regular.woff2`,
      `JetBrainsMono-Medium.woff2`, `JetBrainsMono-SemiBold.woff2`,
      `JetBrainsMono-Bold.woff2`. Place under
      `src/service/socialShare/design/fonts/`.
      Rationale for woff2 (not ttf): same glyph metrics, ~3├Ś smaller on disk,
      same Chromium rendering. The `layout.tsx` uses `next/font/google` for
      the site itself ŌĆö that path is unchanged and unrelated. These four
      files are build-time render inputs only; they never reach `public/`.
- [x] 3b. Verify the font faces load with zero network in DevTools by running
      `file:///ŌĆ”/design.html` in a browser with network throttling set to
      "offline" and confirming the headline glyph metrics match a
      network-online load. This is a manual one-shot check done during
      implementation; it does not become an automated test.

### 4. Build the render pipeline helpers

Read: `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`, `coding-playbook/architecture/folder-structure`, `.aide/docs/progressive-disclosure`

Each of these is an independent helper folder under
`src/service/socialShare/renderOgImage/`. They are written as `.mts` (native
Node ESM TypeScript, run via `node --experimental-strip-types` or compiled ŌĆö
see step 5 Decisions for the exact execution strategy). Each file has JSDoc
on every function, default export, folder name = function name. Playwright's
`chromium`, `Browser`, `Page`, `Locator` types come from `playwright`.

- [x] 4a. `renderOgImage/launchBrowser/index.ts` ŌĆö default export
      `launchBrowser(): Promise<{ browser: Browser; page: Page }>`. Launches
      Chromium headless, opens a new page with viewport `{ width: 1200,
      height: 630, deviceScaleFactor: 1 }`. `deviceScaleFactor: 1` is
      non-negotiable ŌĆö 2├Ś would produce a 2400├Ś1200 capture that the
      verify step would reject.
- [x] 4b. `renderOgImage/loadDesignSource/index.ts` ŌĆö default export
      `loadDesignSource(page: Page): Promise<void>`. Resolves the absolute
      path to `design/design.html` relative to this file via `import.meta.url`
      + `fileURLToPath`, converts to a `file://` URL, calls `page.goto` with
      `waitUntil: 'networkidle'`, then awaits `document.fonts.ready` via
      `page.evaluate`. The fonts-ready wait is a belt-and-suspenders guard
      on top of `font-display: block`; the headline's `-1.4px` letter
      spacing is the spec's highest-risk metric if a fallback swaps in mid-
      capture.
- [x] 4c. `renderOgImage/captureOgElement/index.ts` ŌĆö default export
      `captureOgElement(page: Page, outPath: string): Promise<void>`. Calls
      `page.locator('.og').screenshot({ path: outPath, omitBackground: false,
      type: 'png' })`. Selector-based capture (not viewport-clipped) is
      mandated by the spec's Strategy decision #2 ŌĆö the design HTML
      intentionally wraps the card in scaffolding.
- [x] 4d. `renderOgImage/verifyOutput/index.ts` ŌĆö default export
      `verifyOutput(outPath: string): Promise<{ bytes: number; width: number;
      height: number }>`. Reads the PNG file, parses the PNG IHDR chunk (bytes
      16ŌĆō24 after the 8-byte signature) to extract width/height as
      big-endian uint32, `fs.stat` for bytes. Throws a descriptive error if
      any of: `bytes > 307200` (300 ├Ś 1024), `width !== 1200`,
      `height !== 630`, or the PNG signature bytes (`89 50 4E 47 0D 0A 1A 0A`)
      don't match. No image-processing library dependency ŌĆö raw buffer reads
      only. Returns the metrics on success so the orchestrator can log them.

### 5. Wire the render orchestrator and npm scripts

Read: `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`, `coding-playbook/architecture/folder-structure`, `coding-playbook/services/service-layer`

- [x] 5a. `renderOgImage/index.ts` ŌĆö default export
      `renderOgImage(): Promise<void>`. Orchestrator JSDoc narrates the
      pipeline end-to-end. Pipeline sequence:
        1. `launchBrowser()` ŌåÆ `{ browser, page }`
        2. `loadDesignSource(page)`
        3. Resolve `outPath = path.resolve(process.cwd(), 'public/og.png')`
        4. `captureOgElement(page, outPath)`
        5. `browser.close()` (in a `try/finally` around steps 2ŌĆō4 so a
           failure does not leak the Chromium process)
        6. `metrics = await verifyOutput(outPath)`
        7. `console.log` one line of the form `"og.png rendered ŌĆö <w>├Ś<h>,
           <bytes> bytes"` so build logs carry the verification result.
      Any thrown error from a helper bubbles; the surrounding `prebuild`
      script exits non-zero and `next build` aborts. That is the drift gate.
- [x] 5b. Create `src/service/socialShare/renderOgImage/run.mjs` ŌĆö a
      three-line ESM shim that `await import`s the compiled render
      orchestrator and calls it. Rationale: the `prebuild` hook runs before
      `next build`, so no bundler has processed our TypeScript yet. The
      shim lets the npm script point at a stable `.mjs` entry while the
      render logic lives in `.ts` files that are type-checked and testable
      alongside the rest of `src/service/`. The shim compiles TS on the fly
      via `tsx` (already a transitive dep of `@playwright/test`) ŌĆö invoked
      as `node --import tsx ./run.mjs`. If `tsx` is not present directly,
      add it as a devDependency in 5c.
- [x] 5c. Edit `package.json`:
        - Add `"playwright": "^1.50.1"` to `devDependencies` (version
          locked to the existing `@playwright/test`).
        - Add `"tsx": "^4.19.0"` to `devDependencies` if not already
          resolvable.
        - Add `"og:render": "node --import tsx src/service/socialShare/renderOgImage/run.mjs"`
          to `scripts`.
        - Add `"prebuild": "npm run og:render"` to `scripts`. npm
          automatically runs `prebuild` before `build` ŌĆö no other wiring
          needed.
- [x] 5d. Run `npx playwright install chromium` once locally and document
      the command in the module's JSDoc on `renderOgImage/index.ts`
      (not in a README ŌĆö the contract lives with the code). The JSDoc
      note should reference step 6 below as the CI counterpart, so a
      reader following the module's contract sees both halves of the
      browser-install story in one place.

### 6. Install the Chromium browser in CI before build

Read: `coding-playbook/workflow/ci`, `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions`

Without this step, the first deploy after this plan lands fails: GitHub
Actions' `ubuntu-latest` runner has no Chromium binary, so `npm run build`
triggers `prebuild` ŌåÆ `og:render` ŌåÆ `chromium.launch()` ŌåÆ ENOENT. The
install step must sit between `npm ci` and `npm run build`, and it must
use `--with-deps` on Linux to pull the OS libraries Chromium links
against (libnss3, libnspr4, libatk1.0-0, libatspi2.0-0, libxkbcommon0,
libxcomposite1, libxdamage1, libxrandr2, libgbm1, libasound2, etc. ŌĆö
the exact set is managed by the Playwright installer, so we don't
enumerate it in the workflow).

- [x] 6a. Edit `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`. Insert a new step named
      `Install Playwright browsers` between the existing `Install
      dependencies` step (`npm ci`) and the existing `Build` step
      (`npm run build`). The step runs `npx playwright install
      --with-deps chromium`. Use exactly `chromium` (not the default
      all-browsers install) ŌĆö the render pipeline only launches
      Chromium, and pulling Firefox + WebKit triples download time
      and disk footprint for zero benefit.
- [x] 6b. Do NOT add browser caching for v1. Rationale is recorded
      under Decisions. A first pass ships without `actions/cache@v4`;
      if deploy time on the `Install Playwright browsers` step
      exceeds ~60 seconds consistently, caching becomes a follow-up
      task ŌĆö not part of this plan. Keep the workflow diff minimal.
- [x] 6c. Verify the edit by re-reading the workflow file top-to-bottom.
      The job ordering must be: Checkout ŌåÆ Set up Node ŌåÆ Install
      dependencies ŌåÆ Install Playwright browsers ŌåÆ Build ŌåÆ Upload
      Pages artifact. Any other ordering breaks the build: if the
      browser install runs before `npm ci`, `npx` cannot find the
      Playwright CLI; if it runs after `npm run build`, the render
      has already failed.

