### 9. Integration verification against the built output

Read: `coding-playbook/workflow/testing`, `coding-playbook/client/seo`

This step runs the full render + build pipeline and validates against the
spec's `outcomes.desired` ŌĆö file existence, dimensions, byte size, every-
page meta coverage, one-canonical-image rule. The implementor executes
these as shell commands during the session; they are not automated tests
but are the acceptance gate for the plan. Local execution assumes the
one-time `npx playwright install chromium` has already been run on this
machine (per Prerequisites); CI coverage is provided by step 6.

- [x] 9a. Run `npm run og:render` in isolation. Verify it exits 0, writes
      `public/og.png`, and logs the `"og.png rendered ŌĆö 1200├Ś630, <N> bytes"`
      line with N < 307200. If N is close to the ceiling (> 280 KB),
      flag it in Decisions and note follow-up on palette/compression ŌĆö
      do not downgrade the PNG silently.
- [x] 9b. Run `npm run build`. Confirm the `prebuild` hook fires first
      (npm prints `> prebuild`), `og:render` runs, then `next build`
      completes. Check the `out/` directory:
        - `out/og.png` exists (Next copies from `public/`).
        - `out/index.html` contains all of: `og:image` with value
          `https://aidemd.dev/og.png`, `og:image:width` 1200,
          `og:image:height` 630, `og:image:alt` with the Expo alt string,
          `og:title`, `og:description`, `og:site_name`, `og:type` website,
          `twitter:card` summary_large_image, `twitter:image` with the
          canonical URL, `twitter:title`, `twitter:description`.
        - Sample three docs pages (one from each of `docs/`, `docs/agents/`,
          `docs/commands/`) in `out/` and grep the same meta-tag set. Any
          page missing any of those tags is a spec violation under
          `undesired` outcome #3.
        - Grep every `*.html` under `out/` for `og:image` content values
          other than `https://aidemd.dev/og.png`. Zero matches required
          (enforces the one-canonical-card contract).
- [x] 9c. Use Playwright MCP against `http://localhost:3001/og.png` (dev
      server, port 3001, already running per session context ŌĆö do NOT
      start a server). Navigate to the image URL directly in the MCP
      browser, take a screenshot, and side-by-side compare with
      `src/service/socialShare/design/design.html`'s `.og` element in
      the same browser at 1200 CSS width. Visually confirm: chrome bar
      height 46px, three window dots, prompt text, LIVE + v0.1.0 on the
      right; left column carries the `## canonical docs ┬Ę the .aide
      methodology` tag, the `intent is / the source.` headline with the
      second line in `#3d6b4a`, subhead with italicized accents, three
      chips, footer; right column carries the speech bubble and Expo
      waving; four corner registration marks in forest green. Any
      deviation indicates a font or asset resolution failure in the
      render pipeline.
- [x] 9d. Add a one-line entry under the spec's References noting that
      `handoff-bundle/` has been migrated (`mv` destinations listed).
      Do not edit the `.aide` intent body otherwise ŌĆö the spec's
      frontmatter and strategy are already authoritative.

## Decisions

- **Playwright as a devDependency, never a runtime dependency.** The
  `playwright` package is added under `devDependencies` alongside the
  existing `@playwright/test`. The render orchestrator is invoked only by
  the `og:render` npm script (via `prebuild`), never imported by any
  file under `src/app/`. This keeps the static export's runtime footprint
  untouched and prevents Playwright from being traced into the bundle.
  The root intent's "zero runtime Node dependency" rule is load-bearing
  here and this wiring preserves it.

- **Design source lives at `src/service/socialShare/design/`, not in
  `public/` and not at the repo root.** Files under `public/` are emitted
  as routable URLs by the static export ŌĆö `social-share.html` at the
  repo root or under `public/` would leak to `https://aidemd.dev/social-share.html`,
  an explicit violation of the spec's Strategy decision #3 and the
  frontmatter's "design source is build-time input, not a public page"
  guardrail. Files under `src/service/` are never routable under Next's
  App Router. Nesting the design inside the module it belongs to also
  keeps the cascading domain structure honest ŌĆö the module owns every
  artifact it depends on except the shipped `public/expo-wave.png`.

- **Fonts live at `design/fonts/*.woff2`, referenced by relative `@font-face`
  declarations inside `design.html`.** The alternative (shared font files
  at `src/assets/fonts/` referenced by both `layout.tsx` and the design)
  was rejected because `layout.tsx` already uses `next/font/google` for
  JetBrains Mono at runtime ŌĆö the two paths do not need to share disk
  files, and duplicating the woff2 into the design folder localizes the
  social-share module's dependencies. woff2 chosen over ttf for disk
  footprint (~3├Ś smaller) with identical Chromium rendering.
  `font-display: block` (not `swap`) is deliberate: we need the real
  glyphs at screenshot time, not a fallback swap, and the `networkidle`
  wait plus `document.fonts.ready` wait in `loadDesignSource` closes the
  race.

- **`handoff-bundle/` is removed, not retained as a read-only archive.**
  Git history preserves the original files. Keeping a parallel copy at
  the repo root after migration would train future contributors to edit
  the wrong file (the stale copy) instead of the canonical design source
  inside the module. The spec's "regenerating the image is a single
  command" contract depends on there being exactly one design source;
  two copies is two sources of truth, which is zero.

- **Orchestrator exports a metadata config object, not Next `Metadata`
  directly.** `src/service/socialShare/index.ts` exports an
  `OgImageConfig` ŌĆö a plain-data DTO ŌĆö and `layout.tsx` composes that
  config into its own `Metadata` export. This is a service-layer
  discipline decision (services return plain data, not framework types)
  consistent with the playbook's service-layer note. It also keeps the
  social-share module importable by anything that needs the config
  (e.g., a future `generateMetadata` on a docs page that wants the
  title template) without pulling `next` into this module's type graph.

- **PNG only, no WebP fallback.** The spec names PNG as the one canonical
  format. WebP would save bytes but Twitter/X's unfurl path is the
  bottleneck and it prefers PNG; an alternate format multiplies the
  surface where a consumer silently downgrades. Single format, single
  asset, single URL ŌĆö every layer of the pipeline is designed around
  the one-canonical-card contract.

- **Renderer verifies output byte-by-byte, not via an image library.**
  `verifyOutput` parses the PNG IHDR chunk manually and `fs.stat`s the
  file. Adding `sharp` or `pngjs` would pull a native build step into a
  build-time script for three fields we can read with four lines of
  buffer indexing. The verification is a gate (pass/fail), not a
  transform ŌĆö no library buys us anything.

- **`prebuild` hook, not a post-commit hook or a manual step.** The spec
  lists "rendered card drifting from the design source" as an undesired
  outcome, and the only defense the spec accepts is automatic
  regeneration. `prebuild` ties regeneration to `next build`, which is
  the command that produces every deploy artifact. Manual / post-commit
  hooks depend on humans running them; the spec explicitly rejects
  that failure mode.

- **`--with-deps` on the CI Playwright install, not a bare
  `npx playwright install chromium`.** GitHub Actions' `ubuntu-latest`
  image does not ship with every shared library Chromium links against
  (libnss3, libnspr4, libatk1.0-0, libatspi2.0-0, libxkbcommon0,
  libxcomposite1, libxdamage1, libxrandr2, libgbm1, libasound2, and
  friends). A bare install downloads the browser binary but leaves it
  unable to launch, producing a cryptic `error while loading shared
  libraries` at `chromium.launch()` time. `--with-deps` lets the
  Playwright installer `apt-get install` the exact set it needs ŌĆö this
  is Playwright's canonical recommendation for CI and offloads the
  library-set maintenance burden to the upstream tool. The local
  dev-machine instruction in step 5d omits `--with-deps` because macOS
  and Windows resolve these libraries through a different path and the
  flag is a no-op (or warning) there.

- **No browser cache in the CI workflow for v1.** `actions/cache@v4`
  keyed on the `@playwright/test` version from `package.json` would
  shave ~30ŌĆō60 seconds off the browser install on every run by reusing
  `~/.cache/ms-playwright/`. It's a known pattern and it works. But:
  the site deploys on pushes to `main`, not on every PR, so we are not
  paying this cost on a hot loop. The cache introduces one more moving
  part (cache key hashing, cache restore step, confirmation that the
  binary restored under `--with-deps` still has its OS libraries ŌĆö
  which are apt-installed separately from the browser and are NOT
  cached by Playwright's own cache dir). The minimal-diff workflow
  ships first; caching becomes a follow-up if deploy times prove
  painful. If caching is later added, the canonical key is
  `playwright-${{ runner.os }}-${{ hashFiles('package-lock.json') }}`
  scoped to `~/.cache/ms-playwright`, paired with a conditional that
  still runs `--with-deps` when the cache hits (OS libraries aren't
  cached, only the browser binary is).

- **Install `chromium` only, not all browsers.** `npx playwright install
  --with-deps chromium` downloads ~140 MB of Chromium plus its OS
  libraries. The default `npx playwright install` (no browser argument)
  pulls Chromium + Firefox + WebKit ŌĆö roughly 3├Ś the footprint and
  3├Ś the download time ŌĆö for zero benefit here. The render pipeline
  launches Chromium exclusively via `chromium.launch()` in
  `launchBrowser/index.ts`; Firefox and WebKit would never be
  exercised. The narrow install is also the pattern `@playwright/test`
  uses internally when its config specifies only one browser project.

- **Test the pure logic, gate the rendered artifact with build-time
  verification.** Vitest covers `ogImageConfig` and `verifyOutput` (pure
  functions with easy fixtures). The Playwright-driven render is not
  unit-tested ŌĆö mocking `page.locator('.og').screenshot` would test the
  mock, not the capture. The render is instead gated by
  `verifyOutput` at every build: if the generated PNG is not 1200├Ś630
  PNG under 300 KB, `next build` aborts. This is the same pattern
  `docs-verify.mjs` uses for the docs registry ŌĆö a build-time check
  that runs against real output.

- **Playbook notes referenced in Read lists are:**
  `coding-playbook/foundations/conventions` (naming, JSDoc, helper
  placement, progressive disclosure), `coding-playbook/architecture/folder-structure`
  (orchestrator/helper pattern, cascading domain structure, horizontal
  isolation), `coding-playbook/services/service-layer` (services return
  plain data, no framework types), `coding-playbook/client/seo`
  (App Router `metadata` patterns, per-page override semantics),
  `coding-playbook/workflow/testing` (Vitest co-location, factory
  functions, module-level mocks), `coding-playbook/workflow/ci`
  (GitHub Actions step ordering, install-before-build contracts,
  minimal-diff workflow edits).
